Files: services/auth-service/src/index.js, services/identity-service/src/index.js

Both services fall back to the literal string "dev_secret" when JWT_SECRET
is not set. This makes every JWT trivially forgeable on a misconfigured deploy.

Implementation:
- Remove all || "dev_secret" fallbacks from issueJWT() and requireAuth()
- On service startup add:

    const JWT_SECRET = process.env.JWT_SECRET;
    if (!JWT_SECRET) {
      console.error('FATAL: JWT_SECRET environment variable is not set');
      process.exit(1);
    }

- Apply the same crash-fast pattern to JWT_PUBLIC_KEY

File: services/identity-service/src/index.js

The mfa_secret column comment says "Encrypted TOTP secret" but the code
stores and retrieves it as raw plaintext. pgp_sym_encrypt is never called.

Implementation:
- Encrypt in Node.js using AES-256-GCM before any SQL parameter is set:

    const { createCipheriv, randomBytes, createDecipheriv } = require('crypto');

    function encrypt(plaintext) {
      const iv = randomBytes(12);
      const cipher = createCipheriv('aes-256-gcm', Buffer.from(process.env.AES_KEY, 'hex'), iv);
      const ciphertext = Buffer.concat([cipher.update(plaintext, 'utf8'), cipher.final()]);
      const tag = cipher.getAuthTag();
      return Buffer.concat([iv, tag, ciphertext]).toString('base64');
    }

    function decrypt(blob) {
      const buf = Buffer.from(blob, 'base64');
      const iv = buf.slice(0, 12);
      const tag = buf.slice(12, 28);
      const ciphertext = buf.slice(28);
      const decipher = createDecipheriv('aes-256-gcm', Buffer.from(process.env.AES_KEY, 'hex'), iv);
      decipher.setAuthTag(tag);
      return decipher.update(ciphertext) + decipher.final('utf8');
    }

- Call encrypt() before INSERT, call decrypt() after SELECT
- The database sees only opaque base64 blobs — the key never appears in SQL
- Add AES_KEY to .env.example as a required 64-char hex string
- Write a one-time migration script that reads every existing plaintext
  mfa_secret, encrypts it, and writes the ciphertext back

File: services/websocket-service/src/index.js

Auth tokens are extracted from the URL query string: url.searchParams.get("token").
Tokens in URLs appear in NGINX access logs, browser history, and Referer headers.

Implementation:
- Add a POST /api/v1/auth/ws-ticket endpoint to auth-service:

    app.post('/api/v1/auth/ws-ticket', requireAuth, async (req, res) => {
      const ticket = require('crypto').randomBytes(32).toString('hex');
      await redis.set('ws-ticket:' + ticket, req.user.id, 'EX', 10);
      res.json({ ticket });
    });

- In websocket-service, on new connection extract the ticket from the query
  string (not a JWT), call redis.getdel('ws-ticket:' + ticket) to retrieve
  and atomically delete it in one operation
- If the ticket is missing, expired, or already used, close the connection
  with code 1008 (policy violation)
- The frontend must request a fresh ticket from /auth/ws-ticket immediately
  before opening each WebSocket connection

File: services/webhook-service/src/index.js

Webhook URLs are validated only for syntax. Internal IPs, cloud metadata
endpoints, and service hostnames are not blocked.

Implementation:
- Install the dns module (built-in Node.js)
- Add this validation function and call it on both registration and delivery:

    const { Resolver } = require('dns').promises;

    async function validateWebhookUrl(rawUrl) {
      const parsed = new URL(rawUrl);

      if (parsed.protocol !== 'https:') {
        throw new Error('Only HTTPS webhooks are permitted');
      }

      const resolver = new Resolver();
      const addresses = await resolver.resolve4(parsed.hostname);

      const blockedRanges = [
        /^127\./,
        /^10\./,
        /^192\.168\./,
        /^172\.(1[6-9]|2\d|3[01])\./,
        /^169\.254\./,
        /^0\./
      ];

      for (const ip of addresses) {
        if (blockedRanges.some(pattern => pattern.test(ip))) {
          throw new Error('Webhook URL resolves to a private or reserved address');
        }
      }
    }

- Call validateWebhookUrl() at registration time and again immediately before
  each delivery attempt (DNS rebinding protection — the DNS result can change
  between registration and delivery)
- Return 422 with a safe error message if validation fails

