File: infrastructure/docker-compose.yml, infrastructure/db/init.sql,
all service database connection configs

All 18 services share the same DATABASE_URL. This is tight coupling
that makes independent scaling and deployment impossible.

Implementation:
- In init.sql, create a separate schema per service domain:

    CREATE SCHEMA identity_svc;
    CREATE SCHEMA wallet_svc;
    CREATE SCHEMA compliance_svc;
    CREATE SCHEMA trade_svc;
    CREATE SCHEMA fiat_svc;
    CREATE SCHEMA billing_svc;
    CREATE SCHEMA kyb_svc;
    CREATE SCHEMA notification_svc;
    CREATE SCHEMA analytics_svc;

- Create a dedicated PostgreSQL role per service:

    CREATE ROLE identity_app LOGIN PASSWORD '...';
    GRANT USAGE ON SCHEMA identity_svc TO identity_app;
    GRANT SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE ON ALL TABLES IN SCHEMA identity_svc TO identity_app;

- Update each service's DATABASE_URL to include the schema:
  ?search_path=identity_svc (replace with each service's own schema)
- Move each service's tables into its own schema in init.sql

File: smart-contracts/contracts/AegisTradeEscrow.sol

Escrow IDs are generated using block.timestamp, which miners can manipulate
by a few seconds.

Implementation:
- Add a nonce mapping: mapping(address => uint256) public nonces;
- Replace the ID generation with:

    bytes32 escrowId = keccak256(
      abi.encodePacked(msg.sender, nonces[msg.sender], tradeReference)
    );
    nonces[msg.sender]++;

- Remove block.timestamp from the ID generation entirely

File: infrastructure/nginx/gateway.conf

NGINX listens only on port 80. The Strict-Transport-Security header is
being sent over plain HTTP where browsers ignore it entirely. All JWTs
and financial payloads transit the network unencrypted.

Implementation:
- For production: terminate TLS at the AWS ALB and let NGINX receive plain
  HTTP on port 80 from the ALB's internal target group only
- For staging/self-hosted: add a proper SSL server block:

    server {
      listen 443 ssl;
      ssl_certificate     /etc/ssl/certs/aegis.crt;
      ssl_certificate_key /etc/ssl/private/aegis.key;
      ssl_protocols       TLSv1.2 TLSv1.3;
      ssl_ciphers         HIGH:!aNULL:!MD5;
      ssl_session_cache   shared:SSL:10m;
      add_header Strict-Transport-Security "max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains" always;
    }

- HTTP redirect block — use 302 on first deploy, switch to 301 only after
  confirming HTTPS is stable:

    server {
      listen 80;
      return 302 https://$host$request_uri;
    }

- Remove the HSTS header from the HTTP block entirely (ignored there)
- Move HSTS to the HTTPS server block only

