    upstream websocket_service_ws   { server websocket-service:3099; }

- Add location blocks for each with rate limiting applied
- For the WebSocket service, the WS location block must include upgrade headers:

    location /ws/ {
      proxy_pass http://websocket_service_ws;
      proxy_http_version 1.1;
      proxy_set_header Upgrade $http_upgrade;
      proxy_set_header Connection "upgrade";
      proxy_set_header Host $host;
      proxy_read_timeout 3600s;
    }

File: services/scheduler-service/src/index.js

Two cron jobs fire without any distributed locking. In a multi-instance
deployment they execute simultaneously, producing duplicate Kafka events
and potentially double-executing payments.

Implementation:

    async function withLock(redisClient, lockKey, ttlMs, fn) {
      const acquired = await redisClient.set(lockKey, '1', 'NX', 'PX', ttlMs);
      if (!acquired) {
        console.log('Skipped job ' + lockKey + ' — another instance holds the lock');
        return;
      }
      try {
        await fn();
      } finally {
        await redisClient.del(lockKey);
      }
    }

    cron.schedule('*/5 * * * *', () =>
      withLock(redis, 'lock:recurring-payments', 4 * 60 * 1000, processRecurringPayments)
    );

    cron.schedule('0 2 * * *', () =>
      withLock(redis, 'lock:daily-settlement', 23 * 60 * 60 * 1000, processDailySettlement)
    );

- The TTL (4 minutes for 5-minute job, 23 hours for daily job) is slightly
  shorter than the interval so a crashed instance releases the lock before
  the next tick
- Add a comment: Redis SET NX PX provides automatic TTL expiry as a crash
  recovery mechanism — if the process dies mid-job the lock expires naturally

File: services/trading-service/src/index.js

Both trading-service and scheduler-service query the same recurring_payments
table on the same schedule. This creates guaranteed double-execution on
every tick even without horizontal scaling.

Implementation:
- Delete the cron.schedule("*/5 * * * *") block from trading-service entirely
- trading-service must become a Kafka consumer only:

    consumer.subscribe({ topic: 'payments.recurring.due' });
    consumer.run({
      eachMessage: async ({ message }) => {
        const payment = JSON.parse(message.value.toString());
        await executeRecurringPayment(payment);
      }
    });

- scheduler-service is the sole publisher to payments.recurring.due
- Document this in SERVICES.md: scheduler-service owns all cron scheduling.
  No other service may schedule recurring jobs independently.

File: smart-contracts/contracts/AegisTradeEscrow.sol and all .sol files,
